  "tips": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "topic": "plastic_bag_request_could",
      "content": "The book notes that 'Mógłbym/Mogłabym prosić o reklamówkę?' can be used for 'Could I have a plastic bag, please?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "topic": "brac_present_tense_reference",
      "content": "If you want to revise the conjugation of 'brać' (to take) in the present tense, the book points back to Chapter 20, Note on Sentence 9."
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "topic": "idziemy_irregular_go",
      "content": "'Idziemy' is the irregular present form of the verb 'iść' (to go) for 'we'."
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "topic": "w_galerii_handlowej_locative",
      "content": "In this context, after 'w' use the locative case. 'W centrum handlowym / w tej galerii handlowej' uses the locative."
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "topic": "na_gorze_na_dole",
      "content": "Useful location pair:",
      "examples": [
        "na górze = upstairs",
        "na dole = downstairs"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "topic": "ksiegarnia_plural_book_points_elsewhere",
      "content": "'Księgarnie' is the plural of 'księgarnia' (bookshop / bookstore). The book notes that more on plural noun forms appears elsewhere."
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "topic": "znizka_synonym_rabat",
      "content": "'Zniżka' can also mean discount; it is treated here as a synonym of 'rabat'.",
      "examples": [
        "kupiłem nowy telewizor ze zniżką 15% = I bought a new TV set with a 15% discount"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "topic": "na_targu",
      "content": "'Na targu' means 'at the market'."
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "topic": "zamowienie",
      "content": "'Zamówienie' is an order, derived from 'zamawiać / zamówić'."
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "topic": "organizowac_accusative",
      "content": "After the verb 'organizować' (to organise), use the accusative case."
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "topic": "mozna",
      "content": "'Można' means 'one can' or 'it is possible'."
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "topic": "card_payment_confirmation",
      "content": "When paying by card in Poland, you may be asked to confirm the amount. After the transaction is processed, 'potwierdzenie' here means confirmation. Usually you can simply reply 'Nie, dziękuję' if you do not need that confirmation slip."
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "topic": "stac_w_kolejce",
      "content": "Remember the phrase:",
      "examples": [
        "stać w kolejce do kasy = to stand in a queue at the checkout"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 21,
      "topic": "kasjerka_and_sprzedawca_gender",
      "content": "'Kasjerka' is the feminine form of cashier. 'Sprzedawca' refers to a male shop assistant, and 'sprzedawczyni' to a female shop assistant."
    },
    {
      "id": 23,
      "topic": "drogeria",
      "content": "'Drogeria' is not the same as a pharmacy in English usage. It usually refers to a shop selling cosmetics, toiletries, cleaning products, and similar items."
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "topic": "po_plus_accusative_or_genitive_examples",
      "content": "In sentence 24, 'po' shows purpose ('going to the confectionery shop to buy some cake'). The note also gives parallel examples:",
      "examples": [
        "Idę do apteki po syrop. = I'm going to the pharmacy to buy some syrup.",
        "Cukierni is the genitive after the preposition 'do'."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 28,
      "topic": "locative_after_w",
      "content": "Usually, the locative case is used after the preposition 'w'."
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "topic": "dlaczego_vs_dlatego",
      "content": "The words 'dlaczego' and 'dlatego' are often confused by learners. 'Dlaczego' means why, and 'dlatego' means that's why / therefore.",
      "examples": [
        "Dlaczego tak mówisz? = Why are you saying that?",
        "Pada deszcz. Dlatego nie poszliśmy do parku. = It was raining. That's why we didn't go to the park."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 33,
      "topic": "supermarkecie_locative",
      "content": "'Supermarkecie' is the locative of the noun 'supermarket'."
    },
    {
      "id": 33,
      "topic": "oferowac_accusative",
      "content": "After the verb 'oferować' (to offer), use the accusative case."
    }
  ],
